<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1921-08-23T09:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1921-08-23T09:00:00-05:00" n="467" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d467">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">893.102 Ic/22: Telegram</note>
                        <head><hi rend="italic">The Chargé in China</hi> (<persName type="from"><hi rend="italic">Ruddock</hi></persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the
                                    <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss></hi></head>
                        <opener><dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Peking</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1921-08-23T22:00:00+08:00"><hi rend="italic">August 23,
                                        1921—10 p.m.</hi></date><lb/>[Received August 24—6:52
                                a.m.]</dateline></opener>
                        <p>295. My 288, August 16th, 5 p.m. Diplomatic body today accepted
                            Department’s proposals with the proviso that they may apply
                            retroactively to Ichang and Wuchang mutinies and on understanding <pb facs="0640" n="516" xml:id="pg_516"/> that diplomatic body as a
                            whole will support claims for punitive damages of the nationals of a
                            particular country injured by proscribed official. Does Department
                            approve? Dean of the diplomatic corps delaying note to Foreign Office.
                            Requests your reply within three days.</p>
                        <closer><signed><hi rend="smallcaps">Ruddock</hi></signed></closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>